    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-03-29T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-03-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="630"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d630">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.00/6672: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The President of the Technical Board</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stevens</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Harbin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-03-29">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 29, 1920</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>[Received April 2—5:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>[From Smith:]</p>
                <p>March 29, 6 p.m. Chita. Colonel Blunt<note n="74" xml:id="d630fn74">Of the
                        Russian Railway Service Corps, detained by the Bolsheviks west of Irkutsk;
                        see telegram of Jan. 20 from the Consul at Harbin, <ref target="#pg_530">p.
                            530</ref>.</note> arrived at Chita to-day. I read to him my past
                    telegrams about the Reds. He fully concurs and adds following: Reds treated them
                    very well. All illiterate under 35 years must attend school 2 hours daily, upon
                    taking town inhabitants must clean streets and railways, women work 1 hour to
                    show willingness, towns clean, no one allowed to live in cars, food situation
                    improving everywhere, nullification of money caused some trouble soon adjusted,
                    none of the reports about peasants fighting Reds true. Reds anxious to make
                    working agreement with America and to obtain supplies, also that America send
                    some one to study conditions in Russia. Blunt says leaders honest, industrious,
                    businesslike in their methods and have confidence of all classes except
                    speculators. … Smith.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stevens</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
